        "reflection": "This letter to Ephesus might be the most quietly terrifying of the seven, because the church looks so healthy. Jesus starts by commending them for almost everything — they work hard, they endure, they test false teachers and refuse them. By every external measure, this is a strong church. And then the blow lands: but I have this against you, you've abandoned the love you had at first. I don't want you to miss what he's naming. It isn't a doctrinal failure or a moral scandal. It's a heart that's gone cold slowly, over years of doing the right things for reasons that quietly drained of love. They kept every form of faithfulness and lost the first thing — the love for Jesus that started all of it. And this is the most dangerous kind of decay, because it's invisible from the outside. You can be completely correct and completely cold. You can serve faithfully and feel nothing. You can defend the faith and have no fire for the person the faith is even about. Jesus doesn't congratulate them on their precision — he calls it falling. But the way back is gentle and clear: remember where you were, turn around, and do the first things you did when you actually loved him.",
        "reflectionQ1": "Over the last month, what has your love for Jesus actually looked like — not your activity, not your knowledge, but real warmth for him?",
        "reflectionQ2": "Ephesus kept the activity and lost the love. Name one thing you do for God that's gone routine, and do it from love today.",
        "prayerPrompt": "Tell Jesus honestly where your affection for him is right now — not the answer you think you should give, but the real one — and ask him to restore what has gone cold."
