        "reflection": "Of all seven letters, the one to Laodicea might hit closest to home, because it's the most modern. Laodicea was the richest city around, and the church mirrored it — they lacked nothing, and they knew it. Jesus' diagnosis is brutal: you say I'm rich, I've prospered, I need nothing — and you don't realize you're wretched, pitiable, poor, blind, and naked. I don't want you to miss that the problem here isn't wickedness. It's comfort that's curdled into self-sufficiency. When you have everything you need, the urgency of prayer quietly dries up. When life is stable and managed, the desperate need for God fades into background noise. That's the lukewarm temperature Jesus is talking about — not the heat of someone who hates him, but the room-temperature contentment of someone who has enough and feels no hunger for more. And his reaction is striking: not anger, nausea. Then he offers them the very things they assume they already have — gold refined in fire, white clothes, salve for their eyes. And after the most scathing letter in the book, he does something tender: he stands at the door and knocks. Still pursuing. Still offering. Still there, asking to come back in.",
        "reflectionQ1": "Where has comfort, stability, or success quietly replaced your urgency for God — and what has that slow cooling cost your faith?",
