        "reflection": "Revelation 4 is the hinge the whole book turns on, so slow down here. John steps through an open door into heaven, and the first thing he sees isn't streets of gold — it's a throne, and someone sitting on it. I don't want you to miss how steadying that is. Reality isn't random or up for grabs. It's governed. Someone is at the center, and it isn't you. Around the throne, living creatures never stop saying holy, holy, holy — worship there isn't an event that ends but the permanent response of everything that finally sees God for who he is. And the elders take the crowns off their own heads and throw them down, because everything they hold was given to them in the first place. For churches that felt like Rome was running the world, this is the perspective that changes everything: the world that looks like it's in someone else's hands is actually one where God is on the throne. The suffering is real. The throne is more real. If you're anxious or confused about whether God is actually in control, this chapter is the answer — not an explanation of why things are the way they are, but a vision of who's holding it all together. So the only fitting move is the elders' move: take your small crown off and lay it down.",
        "reflectionQ1": "Where are you living as if there's no throne — carrying outcomes as though they depend entirely on you?",
