        "reflection": "Chapter 5 opens with a crisis: there's a sealed scroll in God's right hand, and no one is found worthy to open it. John weeps — loudly. Then an elder tells him to stop: the Lion of Judah has conquered. But when John turns to see the Lion, what he actually sees is a Lamb, standing as though it had been slain. I don't want you to miss that swap, because it's the heart of the whole book. The most powerful being in the universe, the only one worthy to open history itself, is a slain Lamb still bearing his wounds. God's power doesn't work the way we assume — it wins through sacrifice, not force. He rules through the wounds, not in spite of them. And notice the scars are still there. Jesus didn't leave the cross behind when he went to the throne; he carried it with him. So if you're suffering, here's what this means — the one who governs everything is not a distant power untouched by pain. He's a Lamb who was killed and is alive, carrying the marks to prove he's been exactly where you are. The cross that looked like total defeat is the very thing the whole universe will one day fall down and call worthy.",
        "reflectionQ1": "Where have you been reading your suffering as proof that God is absent — and what changes if the one on the throne carries wounds?",
