        "reflection": "The last chapters of Revelation aren't mainly about escaping to heaven. They're about a new creation — a new heaven and a new earth, with the new Jerusalem coming down out of heaven. I don't want you to miss the direction of that. It's not humanity climbing up to God; it's God coming down to us. The dwelling of God is with man. He will live with them. That's the whole Bible arriving at its final page — God with us, made permanent and unbreakable. And read the specific promises slowly, because they aren't vague comfort: he will wipe every tear from their eyes, death will be no more, and mourning and crying and pain will be no more. That's the undoing of everything the fall ever broke. Everything you're grieving — in the world, in your body, in your relationships, in the dreams that didn't survive — is on a trajectory toward repair. The one on the throne says, behold, I am making all things new. Not all new things — all things new. The same creation, healed. The same history, redeemed. That's the direction everything is moving, and knowing it changes how you carry everything in the meantime. The brokenness is real. But it does not get the last word.",
