        "reflection": "Isaiah 40 is one of the most majestic passages in all of Scripture about who God is. The prophet describes a God who measures the oceans in the hollow of his hand and weighs the mountains on a scale, before whom whole nations are like a drop in a bucket. And then, in a single breath in verse 11, the tone completely changes — this same God gathers the lambs in his arms and gently leads those who are nursing their young. I don't want you to miss that turn, because it's not accidental. Isaiah wants you to hold both at once: the God of infinite cosmic power, and the God who slows his pace for a nursing mother. That word gently means careful attention, a deliberate slowing down, a shepherd matching his stride to the most vulnerable in the flock. God doesn't expect the same pace from an exhausted, nursing mother that he expects from anyone else. He knows exactly what you're carrying. He adjusts to it. Your depletion isn't invisible to the God who formed you — it registers with him, and his response isn't to push you harder. It's to walk slower, right beside you.",
        "reflectionQ1": "What has the relentlessness of this season cost you — in your sense of self, your faith, your ability to feel anything but empty?",
        "reflectionQ2": "Isaiah says God leads nursing mothers gently. Name one expectation you're holding yourself to that he isn't, and lay it down today.",
